TY  - JOUR
AU  - Joyce, Michael A. S.
AU  - Kaminska, Iryna
AU  - Lildholdt, Peter
T1  - Understanding the Real Rate Conundrum: An Application of No-Arbitrage Models to the UK Real Yield Curve*
PY  - 2012
Y1  - 2012/07/01
DO  - 10.1093/rof/rfr012
JO  - Review of Finance
JA  - Rev Financ
VL  - 16
IS  - 3
SP  - 837
EP  - 866
SN  - 1572-3097
AB  - During 2004 and 2005, long-horizon interest rates fell sharply in major international government bond markets (Greenspan's “conundrum”). This common fall mainly reflected lower long real rates. To investigate possible causes, the authors apply a no-arbitrage affine modeling framework to understanding the UK real term structure. The authors find that time-varying term premia are important in explaining movements in long real forward rates. And, although there is evidence that long-horizon expected short real rates declined over the conundrum period, the authors’ results suggest that lower term premia played the dominant role. This could be consistent with the so-called “search for yield” and excess liquidity explanations for the conundrum.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rof/rfr012
ER  - 



